## Test coverage gaps

`tests/reconciler.rs` says outright in its own header comment: *"This is a starting set covering the specific gaps the review flagged, not a complete suite — there's plenty more surface (portals, refs, router, context) that would benefit from the same treatment."* Below is that promised follow-up, plus a pass over the rest of the suite:

- **`src/bindings.rs` (894 lines, the entire JS-facing surface) has no dedicated test file at all.** No test imports `micro_react::bindings` directly. Concretely untested:
  - `create_element` / `createElement`: key coercion for numeric/boolean keys, Fragment-symbol detection, `ref` extraction via `js_ref_to_node_ref`, the variadic-children-array workaround, and the "any non-array child becomes a one-element array" branch.
  - Every `js_use_*` hook wrapper (`js_use_state`, `js_use_reducer`, `js_use_effect`, `js_use_layout_effect`, `js_use_ref`, `js_use_memo`, `js_use_callback`, `js_use_id`) as called *from JS values* — i.e. the JsValue marshalling layer, not just the underlying Rust hook (which `hooks_scheduler.rs` does cover). In particular: `js_use_state`'s functional-updater path (`setState(prev => next)`) resolving against the live cell rather than a stale snapshot, and `cached_setter`/`SETTER_CACHE` actually caching (same setter identity across re-renders) and evicting on unmount.
  - `js_create_context`/`js_use_context`: the Provider/Consumer/`useContext` object shape, the `record_create_context_call` leak-count warning firing on the 2nd+ call, and the `js_use_context` error path when handed something without a `useContext` method.
  - `js_memo`/`shallow_equal`: skip vs. re-render on prop equality, custom `compare` function path, and that a *skipped* render replays the previously-cached vnode via a **fresh** `vnode_to_js` box rather than re-handing out the old one (the comment above `prev_result` flags this as a real double-free risk if gotten wrong — exactly the kind of thing that deserves a regression test, not just a comment).
  - `js_create_error_boundary`/`js_create_error_boundary_inner`: the re-entrancy guard (`in_progress`) actually blocking a nested synchronous re-entrant call, and `ResetOnDrop` clearing the guard after a panic.
  - `js_to_vnode`/`vnode_to_js`/`children_to_js`/`js_val_to_prop_val`/`props_to_js_object`: round-tripping every `PropVal` variant, array-as-fragment, and the `__mrVNode`/`__id` marker protocol.
  - The `VNODE_STORE` leak-guard: nothing asserts that `take_vnode` is idempotent (second call on the same id returns `None`, doesn't panic/double-free) or that the `VNODE_STORE_WARN_THRESHOLD` warning actually fires once and only once.
- **Portals** (`diff.rs::diff_portal`, `VNodeInner::Portal` in `vnode.rs`) have no test coverage anywhere in `tests/`. Nothing exercises rendering into a foreign container, moving a portal's target container across renders, or unmounting a component whose subtree contains a portal.
- **Refs** have only `refs_dom.rs` (9 tests) via the Rust-level `NodeRef` API; none of it goes through `bindings::js_ref_to_node_ref`, so the callback-ref vs. object-ref (`{ current }`) branches, and re-syncing a ref when the underlying DOM node is replaced (same slot, different tag), are untested from the JS-facing side.
- **`router.rs`** (495 lines) has 22 tests but per the `reconciler.rs` note is flagged as under-covered — check in particular: nested routes / relative paths, redirect components, and interaction with `ErrorBoundary` (a route component throwing).
- **`src/scan.rs`** (`scan_tag_name_end`, `skip_js_string`, `skip_js_comment`, `find_matching_brace`) has no dedicated unit-test file; it's only exercised indirectly through `jsx_test.rs`'s higher-level transpile assertions. Edge cases worth pinning down directly: unterminated strings/comments (should return `None`, not panic or scan past the end), nested braces inside a JS string literal inside a `{}` hole, and block vs. line comments abutting a tag boundary.
- **`src/render.rs`** (`Root::render`/`Root::unmount`) has no dedicated test file; it's only touched incidentally through `refs_dom.rs` and other DOM tests calling `Root::render` to get a mounted tree, never testing `Root` itself — e.g. re-`render()`-ing on the same root with a changed tree, or `unmount()` correctly tearing down all effect cleanups/hooks for the whole tree (not just a single component, which is what `hooks_scheduler.rs` covers).
- **`scheduler.rs::MAX_FLUSH_ITERATIONS` bailout path** (the "component re-dirties itself forever" guard) is `pub` specifically so tests can assert the exact bailout point per its own doc comment, but no test in `tests/` actually does — `hooks_scheduler.rs` covers normal flush behavior but not the runaway-loop / `schedule_flush_deferred` fallback-to-`setTimeout` path.
- **`hooks.rs::report_to_nearest_boundary`'s two lookup paths** (`nearest_boundary` on the origin instance vs. falling back to the live `BOUNDARY_STACK`) are both exercised together in the mainline boundary tests, but the specific case the doc comment calls out — a component's *own later, independent* re-render (its own `setState`, not triggered from within the boundary's active diff pass) still finding its ancestor boundary via the persisted field when `BOUNDARY_STACK` is empty — doesn't appear to have its own isolated test.

## Plans for extension

- **No `forwardRef`-equivalent** — `ref` is only extracted and attached at the DOM-element level (`create_element`'s `node_ref`); there's no mechanism for a function/HOC-wrapped component to forward a `ref` prop through to an inner DOM node the way `React.forwardRef` does. Not fixed here: this needs a real API design decision (a `forwardRef(fn)` wrapper type distinct from a plain component function, threaded through `create_element`/`js_ref_to_node_ref` in `bindings.rs`), not a local patch.

## Design/soundness notes

- **Raw-pointer hook dispatch (`hooks.rs`)**: `CURRENT_INST` is a `*mut ComponentInst` used via macros (`hooks_ref!`, `hooks_get_mut`, etc.) with `unsafe` blocks justified by "WASM is single-threaded, inst is valid for the render's duration." That's true today, but it's a hard invariant resting entirely on nothing calling back into JS in a way that could re-enter and mutate `hooks` while a `&mut` slot reference from `hooks_get_mut` (which is literally `&'static mut`, an aggressive lifetime cheat) is alive. The reentrant-render handling (`render_generation`) suggests the author is aware of this risk and has thought about it, but this is the single place I'd want the most scrutiny/fuzzing before trusting it in production, since the failure mode of getting it wrong is silent UB, not a panic.
- **`VNODE_STORE`**: raw `Box::into_raw`/`from_raw` was deliberately avoided in favor of an id-keyed map with idempotent removal — good instinct — but the "leak guard" only *warns* at 10,000 unconsumed entries via console; it doesn't actually reclaim anything. If a JS caller repeatedly constructs vnodes it never passes to render (e.g., a conditional branch that discards a built tree), this grows forever with only a log line to notice it.
- **`dangerouslySetInnerHTML`** and the general prop-setting path look correctly scoped (opt-in only, not the default path), and text nodes go through `create_text_node`, so ordinary text content isn't an XSS vector.
